    content: `The first personality test was invented in 1919. Over a century later, we are still taking them. 16Personalities gets 15 million visitors a month. uQuiz gets 280,000. arealme gets 283,000. The numbers have not gone down. They have gone up.

## The Science Problem

Here is the uncomfortable truth: most personality tests are not scientifically valid. The Myers-Briggs Type Indicator, the most famous personality test in the world, has been debunked by psychologists repeatedly. Its test-retest reliability is around 50%, meaning half the people who take it twice get different results. Its four binary dimensions do not correspond to any known psychological model. The company that produces it has never published peer-reviewed validity data.

And yet: millions of people take it every year and feel seen.

## The Receipt Format

We chose the receipt format because receipts are honest. A receipt does not flatter you. It does not tell you that you are special. It lists what you bought and what it cost. Our personality receipts do the same thing: they list your traits and the cost of having them. "Overthinking: 47x, $4.70 each." That is not a diagnosis. It is an accounting.

The receipt format also solves the biggest problem with personality tests: the results are boring. A paragraph of generic praise ("You are a thoughtful and creative individual who values deep connections") applies to literally everyone. A receipt with specific line items ("3 AM Existential Dread: 1x, $13.00") applies to one person.

## Why We Keep Taking Them

Personality tests serve a function that has nothing to do with accuracy. They give us language for things we feel but cannot articulate. Before you took the test, you knew you overthought things. After the test, you have a name for it, a category, a community. "I am an Overthinker" is more useful than "I think about things a lot."

The test also gives us permission. If the test says you are introverted, you have external validation for declining social plans. If it says you are spontaneous, you have permission to book a flight on impulse. The test does not change you. It licenses you.

## The SBTI Precedent

In China, a personality test called SBTI (an MBTI parody) generates over 40 million searches a month. The results are brutally honest, sometimes insulting, and deeply specific. People share them not because they are accurate but because they are funny and relatable. The shareability is the point. A boring, accurate test gets taken once. A funny, inaccurate test gets shared 50 million times.

Our receipts follow this logic. We would rather make you laugh and feel seen than give you a scientifically validated personality profile. The science is not the point. The feeling is.`,
